    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.35"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">35</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        2232 Blake St. #5
                        Berkeley, <hi rend="caps">CA</hi> 94704
                        August 1, 1972
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>My husband and I just got back from our wanderings in the northern California mountains, and were happily surprised to find that my parents had made a tape-recording of your talk on the Dick Cavett show. I t was the first time that I had the chance to hear it and was very excited by it.</p>
                
                <p>I will be getting a grant to continue work on my dissertation on Black Elk during the coming year. Since at the moment we are between houses, I would like to take the occasion to travel your way and have a talk with you. Would you please let me know if this would be convenient for you? We were thinking of coming out in a week or so but would, of course, want to respect your own plans.</p> 
                
                <p>Please give my best regards to Mrs. Young and thank her for lettting me know of the Cavett show re-run.</p> 
                
                <p>I will be looking forward to your answer and hoping that you will have the time available to see us.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Diane De Pisa</signed> 
                    <signed>Diane De Pisa</signed> 
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
